onal veg to, while the peaches can be swapped for nectarines or larger stone fruit. Both recipes are versatile, too.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Mon, 07 Aug 2023 12:00:39 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">entertainment</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/food/2023/aug/07/chowder-sticky-peaches-cream-budget-coconut-milk-recipes-shivi-ramoutar" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2023/aug/07/bidenomics-lessons-labour-looks-to-democrats-as-it-prepares-for-power" target="_blank">Bidenomics lessons: Labour looks to Democrats as it prepares for power</a></h2><div class="description"> Rachel Reeves dismayed many in the green movement this year when she announced a Labour government would phase in its £28bn green growth plan rather than spending the full amount straight away. The shadow chancellor had been mulling such an announcement for a while, but decided on it for sure after being warned two weeks earlier by senior members of the Biden administration not to rush the rollout.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Mon, 07 Aug 2023 13:00:40 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">entertainment</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2023/aug/07/bidenomics-lessons-labour-looks-to-democrats-as-it-prepares-for-power" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2023/aug/07/accessibility-britain-urban-wheelchair-disabled-people" target="_blank">I had no idea how inaccessible urban Britain is – until I faced it in a wheelchair | Dorothy Dunn</a></h2><div class="description"> UN has predicted that two-thirds of the global population will live in cities by 2050. Many features of our urban planning are actively exclusionary – even ableist. By 2050, two thirds of the world's population will be living in cities, says Dorothy Dunn. Transport officials have proposed an array of measures to make British towns and cities more accessible.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Mon, 07 Aug 2023 11:00:38 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">entertainment</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2023/aug/07/accessibility-britain-urban-wheelchair-disabled-people" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2023/aug/07/british-people-kinder-strikes-climate-politiicians-progressive" target="_blank">British people are kinder and less divided than politicians give us credit for | Nesrine Malik</a></h2><div class="description"> On urgent issues from strikes to climate, voters are increasingly progressive. If only our so-called leaders would catch up, they would be more progressive. The result is a widening gulf between people’ reality and what they are told they actually believe in and care about. Immigration has been at the top of the political agenda for the past three decades.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Mon, 07 Aug 2023 05:00:31 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">entertainment</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2023/aug/07/british-people-kinder-strikes-climate-politiicians-progressive" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2023/aug/07/email-dread-pigeons-message-inbox" target="_blank">Email makes my fingers tingle and my stomach drop with dread. Can’t we go back to pigeons? | Emma Beddington</a></h2><div class="description"> Recent research on the ‘best time to send an email has highlighted for me how awful email is all the time. As a new French citizen, perhaps I should insist on my legal right to disconnect out of hours. Ideally, I’d like no work-related emails before 10am, between midday and 2pm, after 6pm.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Mon, 07 Aug 2023 06:00:32 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">entertainment</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2023/aug/07/email-dread-pigeons-message-inbox" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2023/aug/07/tinder-dating-app-subscription-long-term-relationship-love" target="_blank">Tinder wants to sell a $500-a-month subscription. Can they justify that? | Nancy Jo Sales</a></h2><div class="description"> Tinder has announced it is moving ahead with plans to launch a new “high-end” membership for as much as $500 a month. Tinder Vault will provide an “even more fun experience” and “quality matches” for “exclusive” users.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Mon, 07 Aug 2023 12:42:55 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">entertainment</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2023/aug/07/tinder-dating-app-subscription-long-term-relationship-love" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2023/aug/07/harry-potter-and-the-cursed-child-job-of-a-lifetime-why-i-quit" target="_blank">Harry Potter and the Cursed Child was the job of a lifetime, and I walked away from it | Gillian Cosgriff</a></h2><div class="description"> There's an untouchability about something that's supposed to be wondrous that means we shy away from hearing about the full spectrum of the experience. I was cast as Moaning Myrtle in 2018 and took over the role of Delphi in 2020. I stayed with the show for just over three years, performing in Melbourne’s beautiful Princess theatre.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Mon, 07 Aug 2023 09:00:36 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">entertainment</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2023/aug/07/harry-potter-and-the-cursed-child-job-of-a-lifetime-why-i-quit" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2023/aug/07/performing-edinburgh-fringe-georgie-greer" target="_blank">Some people just won’t like you, but don’t take it personally: what surviving the fringe taught me about life | Natalie Haynes</a></h2><div class="description"> It is now 17 years since I took a show to the Edinburgh fringe, but scars run deep. Performing at the festival is hugely stressful, but it was an almost uniquely stressful experience for a young comedian. Even when I was a fringe regular, it was quite common to sell out a month-long run and still sustain losses of £10,000.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Mon, 07 Aug 2023 07:00:33 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">entertainment</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2023/aug/07/performing-edinburgh-fringe-georgie-greer" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2023/aug/07/is-the-climate-crisis-finally-catching-up-with-antarctica-finding-the-answer-has-never-been-more-pressing" target="_blank">Is the climate crisis finally catching up with Antarctica? Finding the answer has never been more pressing | Andrew Meijers</a></h2><div class="description"> The media has been awash with stories of marine heatwaves across the northern hemisphere. The potential collapse of the Atlantic meridional overturning circulation by mid-century is an exemplar of the problem facing researchers. Our inability to confidently predict sea level rise between an extremely challenging two metres and a civilisation-ending 10 metres is an example.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Mon, 07 Aug 2023 02:01:53 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">world</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2023/aug/07/is-the-climate-crisis-finally-catching-up-with-antarctica-finding-the-answer-has-never-been-more-pressing" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/global-development/commentisfree/2023/aug/07/a-pandemic-is-not-just-a-disease-its-a-political-social-and-economic-crisis-fuelled-by-inequality" target="_blank">A pandemic is not just a disease – it’s a crisis fuelled by inequality |  Mia Malan</a></h2><div class="description"> Eight out of 10 stories you produced were about the epidemic during the late 1990s and early 2000s. It was a time of unprecedented Aids-related deaths and activism as fierce as the fight against apartheid. Getting scientists to develop a medicine is a relatively small part of the solution to a pandemic. The more difficult thing is to get the medicine to people who need it.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Mon, 07 Aug 2023 05:30:31 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">health</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/global-development/commentisfree/2023/aug/07/a-pandemic-is-not-just-a-disease-its-a-political-social-and-economic-crisis-fuelled-by-inequality" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2023/aug/06/the-guardian-view-on-invisible-women-cancelled-by-history-restored-with-care" target="_blank">The Guardian view on invisible women: cancelled by history, restored with care | Editorial</a></h2><div class="description"> Eileen O’Shaughnessy made her husband's work possible at the cost of her own. She typed up his writing instead of completing her master's in psychology. Shortly before meeting Orwell she wrote a dystopian poem titled End of the Century, 1984. She suggested that he write an animal fable instead of an essay denouncing Stalinism.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Sun, 06 Aug 2023 17:25:16 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">entertainment</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2023/aug/06/the-guardian-view-on-invisible-women-cancelled-by-history-restored-with-care" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2023/aug/06/the-guardian-view-on-the-digital-divide-a-growing-problem-that-must-be-taken-seriously" target="_blank">The Guardian view on the digital divide: a growing problem that must be taken seriously | Editorial</a></h2><div class="description"> Ministers are complacent about the high price to society of pushing the cost of administering public services on to their users. The danger is that a wall is erected between wider society and a group that tends to live outside England’s south‑east. Citizens Advice said a million people disconnected their broadband in the last year because they couldn’t afford it.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Sun, 06 Aug 2023 17:30:16 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">world</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2023/aug/06/the-guardian-view-on-the-digital-divide-a-growing-problem-that-must-be-taken-seriously" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/society/2023/aug/06/kinship-carers-do-a-vital-job-they-must-get-better-support" target="_blank">Kinship carers do a vital job. They must get better support | Letters</a></h2><div class="description"> Parents have relied on kinship care for centuries. It enables children to grow up within their family, maintaining key relationships. But changing family dynamics are not easy to navigate. Support should be available regardless of the legal status of the arrangement, says CoramBAAF. The government’s nat.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Sun, 06 Aug 2023 15:20:18 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">entertainment</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/society/2023/aug/06/kinship-carers-do-a-vital-job-they-must-get-better-support" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/2023/aug/06/where-do-you-turn-when-your-grief-feels-like-too-much" target="_blank">Where do you turn when your grief feels like too much? | Letters</a></h2><div class="description"> Readers respond to an article by Natalie Morris on the need for nuanced and proportionate support for the bereaved. One thing she didn’t mention is that at a point when you are at your most vulnerable, you also have to deal with the “sadmin” to do with the death.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Sun, 06 Aug 2023 15:20:55 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">entertainment</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/2023/aug/06/where-do-you-turn-when-your-grief-feels-like-too-much" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/football/2023/aug/07/matildas-australia-denmark-last-16-women-s-world-cup-match-report" target="_blank">Caitlin Foord and Hayley Raso fire Australia into quarter-finals with accomplished win over Denmark</a></h2><div class="description"> Australia beat Denmark 2-0 in World Cup quarter-finals on Monday night. Caitlin Foord scored the first of two goals for the Matildas against Denmark. Arsenal attacker grew up just an hour away on Australia's south-east coast. Foord: ‘I still think Sydney can be louder’</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Mon, 07 Aug 2023 12:24:39 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">world</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/football/2023/aug/07/matildas-australia-denmark-last-16-women-s-world-cup-match-report" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/football/2023/aug/07/uswnt-womens-world-cup-2023-exit-reasons-soccer" target="_blank">USA’s World Cup rock bottom was a downfall years in the making | Jeff Kassouf</a></h2><div class="description"> USA's last-16 elimination at the hands of Sweden in Melbourne marked their worst finish at a major tournament. The United States had won four of the last eight World Cups – including the last two – and had never finished worse than third. The Americans were ahead of the pack for years before the rest of the world started to give the women’s game the respect it deserves.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Mon, 07 Aug 2023 12:28:33 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">sports</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/football/2023/aug/07/uswnt-womens-world-cup-2023-exit-reasons-soccer" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/football/2023/aug/06/even-more-proud-to-be-jamaican-reggae-girlz-defy-the-odds-to-reach-world-cup-knockout" target="_blank">‘Even more proud to be Jamaican’: Reggae Girlz defy the odds to reach World Cup knockout</a></h2><div class="description"> Jamaica became the first English-speaking Caribbean country to have made it to the knockout round. The team held off Brazil to become one of the last 16, having overcome indifference and underfunding on the way. Jamaica knocked football superpower Brazil out of the Women’s World Cup last week.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Sun, 06 Aug 2023 21:01:54 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">sports</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/football/2023/aug/06/even-more-proud-to-be-jamaican-reggae-girlz-defy-the-odds-to-reach-world-cup-knockout" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2023/aug/07/bazball-is-battering-winviz-but-heres-why-we-all-hate-sporting-ai-stealing-our-turf" target="_blank">Bazball is battering WinViz, but here’s why we all hate sporting AI stealing our turf | Emma John</a></h2><div class="description"> The influx of data modelling has some positive impact, but please leave the wayward predictions to us flawed humans. On the basis of data synthesised from previous pieces, this column currently has a 51% chance of being a success. Intuitive, AI‑powered analysis can even detect irony fatigue.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Mon, 07 Aug 2023 07:00:33 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">entertainment</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2023/aug/07/bazball-is-battering-winviz-but-heres-why-we-all-hate-sporting-ai-stealing-our-turf" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2023/aug/07/england-announce-rugby-world-cup-squad-with-slade-and-dombrandt-axed" target="_blank">England announce Rugby World Cup squad with Slade and Dombrandt axed</a></h2><div class="description"> England boss Steve Borthwick makes changes to his 33-man squad after Wales loss. Slade, Dombrandt and Joe Cokanasiga all left out of World Cup squad. Joe Marchant, Ben Earl and Henry Arundell among those left out.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Mon, 07 Aug 2023 09:04:29 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">sports</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2023/aug/07/england-announce-rugby-world-cup-squad-with-slade-and-dombrandt-axed" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/football/2023/aug/07/luton-premier-league-2023-24-preview" target="_blank">Premier League 2023-24 preview No 12: Luton</a></h2><div class="description"> Back in the top flight after more than three decades, a tight ground and strong work ethic look the best weapons of survival. Last season’s position was 3rd (Championship) in the Premier League last season. Click here for more Premier League news.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Mon, 07 Aug 2023 11:00:38 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">sports</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/football/2023/aug/07/luton-premier-league-2023-24-preview" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/sport/blog/2023/aug/06/ellie-cardwell-epitomises-englands-spirit-in-netball-world-cup-final" target="_blank">Ellie Cardwell epitomises England’s spirit in Netball World Cup final | Emma John</a></h2><div class="description"> Australia showed why they are the world's best netball team. England's goal shooter Ellie Cardwell scored a goal in the World Cup final. She sunk a shot from halfway back in the circle, and gestured to the crowd to make some noise. England couldn't secure their first title against the world No 1 side, but they still played with adventure.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Sun, 06 Aug 2023 21:12:38 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">sports</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/sport/blog/2023/aug/06/ellie-cardwell-epitomises-englands-spirit-in-netball-world-cup-final" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/football/2023/aug/06/arsenal-mental-block-manchester-city-aaron-ramsdale" target="_blank">Arsenal removed ‘mental block’ with win over City, claims Aaron Ramsdale</a></h2><div class="description"> Aaron Ramsdale hails the removal of a 'mental block' after Arsenal beat Manchester City 4-1 in the Community Shield. The Gunners had lost all three meetings with last season's title rivals. Ramsdale was pivotal to their shootout win, saving from Rodri in the shootout.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Sun, 06 Aug 2023 20:16:58 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">sports</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/football/2023/aug/06/arsenal-mental-block-manchester-city-aaron-ramsdale" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/football/audio/2023/aug/07/efl-arsenal-shake-city-hoodoo-football-weekly-podcast" target="_blank">EFL back with a bang and Arsenal shake City hoodoo - Football Weekly podcast</a></h2><div class="description"> Max Rushden is joined by Ben Fisher, George Elek and Sanny Rudravajhala as domestic football returns. Do the teams relegated from the Premier League remain favourites for a quick return? What shape will their squads be in come the end of the transfer window?</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Mon, 07 Aug 2023 12:17:18 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">sports</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/football/audio/2023/aug/07/efl-arsenal-shake-city-hoodoo-football-weekly-podcast" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2023/aug/06/mathieu-van-der-poel-becomes-world-road-cycling-champion-in-glasgow-protest-crash" target="_blank">Mathieu van der Poel becomes world road cycling champion in Glasgow</a></h2><div class="description"> Dutchman overcomes protest and crash to claim glory. Race had been held up for almost an hour by protesters. Mathieu van der Poel of the Netherlands won an attritional and dramatic men’s UCI World Road Race title in Glasgow, surviving an environmental protest, a high-speed crash and a broken racing shoe.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Sun, 06 Aug 2023 19:01:20 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">sports</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2023/aug/06/mathieu-van-der-poel-becomes-world-road-cycling-champion-in-glasgow-protest-crash" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/sport/99-94-cricket-blog/2023/aug/07/county-cricket-one-day-cup-format-leicestershire-gloucestershire" target="_blank">County cricket: how can we inject some jeopardy to the One-Day Cup?</a></h2><div class="description"> Gary Naylor wonders about the lack of imagination in naming the One-Day Cup groups “A and B” The format needs a rethink – perhaps baseball might help. Leicestershire and Gloucestershire set the early pace, but the format needs to be re-named.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Mon, 07 Aug 2023 11:33:24 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">entertainment</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/sport/99-94-cricket-blog/2023/aug/07/county-cricket-one-day-cup-format-leicestershire-gloucestershire" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2023/aug/07/progress-on-slowing-deforestation-could-boost-climate-efforts-say-experts-aoe" target="_blank">Progress on slowing deforestation could boost climate efforts, say experts</a></h2><div class="description"> Reduction in primary forest loss in Indonesia and Malaysia, as well as Brazil and Colombia, offers hope for tropical forests across the world. Experts say if rich countries provide backing to tropical forested countries it could help governments deliver on Cop26 promises to halt and reverse deforestation by 2030. Leaders from Venezuela to Peru hoping to present a plan at Cop28 to halt their destruction.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Mon, 07 Aug 2023 06:00:33 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">world</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2023/aug/07/progress-on-slowing-deforestation-could-boost-climate-efforts-say-experts-aoe" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2023/aug/06/indigenous-activists-gather-in-brazil-to-discuss-future-of-the-amazon" target="_blank">Indigenous activists gather in Brazil to discuss future of the Amazon</a></h2><div class="description"> Campaigners voice hopes and fears for the rainforest before leaders of eight Amazon nations attend summit in Belém. Two-day conclave will bring together presidents of Brazil, Colombia, Peru and Venezuela. Indigenous activists and environmentalists converged in one of the Amazon's biggest cities.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Sun, 06 Aug 2023 17:17:58 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">entertainment</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2023/aug/06/indigenous-activists-gather-in-brazil-to-discuss-future-of-the-amazon" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2023/aug/06/winter-heatwave-andes-sign-things-come-scientists-warn" target="_blank">Winter heatwave in Andes is sign of things to come, scientists warn</a></h2><div class="description"> Human-caused climate disruption and El Niño push temperature in mountains to 37C. Heatwave in central Chilean Andes melting snow below 3,000 metres (9,840ft) will have knock-on effects for downstream valleys who depend on meltwater during the spring and summer.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Sun, 06 Aug 2023 08:00:05 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">entertainment</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2023/aug/06/winter-heatwave-andes-sign-things-come-scientists-warn" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2023/aug/06/david-suzuki-climate-action-crisis-in-conversation-natasha-mitchell-melbourne-museum" target="_blank">‘Despair is a luxury we can’t afford’: David Suzuki on fighting for action on the climate crisis</a></h2><div class="description"> The celebrated science broadcaster and environmental activist says we have to stop elevating the economy and politics over the state of our world. David Suzuki is in an office overflowing with a mess of boxes, bottles and binders, some barely hanging on to the top shelf. We're speaking via video between his cabin on an island off the Canadian west coast and his home office in southern Tasmania.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Sat, 05 Aug 2023 20:00:51 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">entertainment</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2023/aug/06/david-suzuki-climate-action-crisis-in-conversation-natasha-mitchell-melbourne-museum" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/society/2023/aug/07/uk-mps-warn-use-smart-tech-domestic-abuse" target="_blank">UK MPs warn against growing use of smart tech in domestic abuse</a></h2><div class="description"> Committee’s report says devices including home security systems used to coerce and control victims of domestic abuse. Culture, media and sport committee launched inquiry last year to consider the benefits and harms of connected technology, including virtual assistants and fitness trackers. Report: Devices including smart home security system used to coerced victims of abuse.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Sun, 06 Aug 2023 23:01:24 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">world</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/society/2023/aug/07/uk-mps-warn-use-smart-tech-domestic-abuse" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/business/2023/aug/07/ideal-heating-to-kickstart-electric-heat-pump-production-in-hull" target="_blank">Major UK gas boiler maker to start electric heat pump production in Hull</a></h2><div class="description"> Ideal Heating’s £50m investment aims to build 60,000 pumps and train 5,000 installers a year. It describes it as the biggest transformation since the switch from coal to gas devices in the 1930s. The company has invested £50million in transforming facilities at its Hull headquarters.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Mon, 07 Aug 2023 08:30:16 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">health</span></div><br>